What are the 3 most important products exported by Brazil in the last 5 years?

When considering only the USD variable, the most important products exported from 2015 to 2019 are soybeans, sugar and soybean meal.

What are the main routes through which Brazil have been exporting âcornâ in the last few years? Are there differences in the relative importance of routes depending on the product?

The main two routes for corn exportation over the past ten years have been sea and river, respectively. For the past 10 years the sea route, by far, played the most significant role for the Brazilian exports. Besides the river route for soybeans and corn, all the other routes have had an insignficant participation in delivering Brazilian products to the rest of the world.

For each of the products in the dataset, show the 5 most important states in terms of exports?

What should be the total brazilian soybeans, soybean_meal, and corn export forecasts, in tons, for the next 11 years (2020-2030)?

All forecasts were made using models built on multiple linear regressions in combination with ARIMA. Common Machine Learning methods have no awareness of time dimensions, that is why in this case, simply applying them would not result in a reasonable prediction as the question involve time series data. Even though it is a relatively simple model in comparison with the other models such as boosting, deep learning or even regression trees, the model have been proven a fair performance for the data provided. It is true that the predictions made present a steady growth throughout the years (except for corn and soybean meal in 2020), because the covariates provided evolve in constants rates within the period of time to be predicted. Moreover, the models are based on regression tuned by backward elimination, in other words, the independent variables present a correlation with the dependent variable, and no more than that. For further discussions, a model built on causation diagrams together with data from observational studies and reduction of biases may provide a better understanding of the Brazilian exportsâ performance and, thus, a more accurate model.
